        <p> ___Twig_token_1___ just something like that. Perfect timing: When we arrived, a free leadership was just starting - so spontaneously connected. Actually, it should be in German, but was in English and French. No matter, I still understood most - and I was able to take pictures anyway. The guide lady was really entertaining and obviously enjoyed her job. </p>
        <p> At some point we said goodbye - we finally had to go to the Teide. We should be on the cable car shortly before 3 p.m. So quickly nibbled a few bananas and then go towards the volcano. </p>
        <p> Because our rental car was more of the "snoring nose" category, we decided on the longer but better developed route to the Teide. And that was a good choice. The road was easy to drive, it went well uphill - of course with a few photo stops in between. The landscape reminded a bit of the Uluru in Australia, only less magical. </p>
        <p> When we arrived at the valley station, we still had some time. So first drink something, relax, watch people. The gondolas beforehand were all jam -packed - the greater the joy when we could get in earlier than planned and it was suddenly really empty. </p>

